jurisdiction.title: Roman Catholic Diocese of Joliet Illinois

9F171D69997846A9AC2BC0692C2D9EB9.description:
Relating the choice of measures of center and variability to the shape of the data distribution and the context in which the data was
gathered.

714E533FC30A4F96B05043A75882A123.description:
Giving quantitative measures of center (median and/or mean) and variability (interquartile range and/or mean absolute deviation), as well
as describing any overall pattern and any striking deviations from the overall pattern with reference to the context in which the data was
gathered.

542E66A33EC34CBF94CE004DC8D0B355.description: Describing the nature of the attribute under investigation, including how it was measured and its units of measurement.

2D55A96EBCC34A6DAE4EC59E5FAE238C.description: Summarize numerical data sets in relation to their context, such as by:

F3C31A2F84A14CC2A596154B44D01A03.description: Display numerical data in plots on a number line, including dot plots, histograms, and box plots.

AA04E760DF45433EA3FA66B7D90E06E9.description:
Recognize that a measure of center for a numerical data set summarizes all of its values with a single number, while a measure of variation describes
how its values vary with a single number.

C4FC42BF106C42CFA85B26EF85562CB5.description:
Understand that a set of data collected to answer a statistical question has a distribution which can be described by its center, spread, and overall
shape.

1D766E796EAB4C60BF986E5E8A509D95.description:
Recognize a statistical question as one that anticipates variability in the data related to the question and accounts for it in the answers. For example,
“How old am I?” is not a statistical question, but “How old are the students in my school?” is a statistical question because one anticipates variability
in students’ ages.

757564A568E94080A8DA53504494BFC2.description:
Represent three-dimensional figures using nets made up of rectangles and triangles, and use the nets to find the surface area of these figures. Apply
these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

098AAB340ECF44CFB8DC13F3258C3BF7.description:
Draw polygons in the coordinate plane given coordinates for the vertices; use coordinates to find the length of a side joining points with the same
first coordinate or the same second coordinate. Apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

CE7B40CCF3B7478BAEDEB16A96CD6481.description:
Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with fractional edge lengths by packing it with unit cubes of the appropriate unit fraction edge lengths,
and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths of the prism. Apply the formulas V = l w h and V = b h to
find volumes of right rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

9D6EA935944042DAA1CBBC703BE6E7CA.description:
Find area of right triangles, other triangles, special quadrilaterals, and polygons by composing into rectangles or decomposing into triangles and
other shapes; apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

D101154686C14BE49BF43A77C2043D16.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving area, surface area, and volume.

30EA9F5DB9184B949CC50638C709F36E.description:
Use variables to represent two quantities in a real-world problem that change in relationship to one another; write an equation to express one
quantity, thought of as the dependent variable, in terms of the other quantity, thought of as the independent variable. Analyze the relationship
between the dependent and independent variables using graphs and tables, and relate these to the equation. For example, in a problem involving
motion at constant speed, list and graph ordered pairs of distances and times, and write the equation d = 65t to represent the relationship between
distance and time.

C32556A3AB3F403F85A73F5242A06B51.description: Represent and analyze quantitative relationships between dependent and independent variables.

DC39C0CAB09043278B16AD632259673D.description:
Write an inequality of the form x > c or x < c to represent a constraint or condition in a real-world or mathematical problem. Recognize that
inequalities of the form x > c or x < c have infinitely many solutions; represent solutions of such inequalities on number line diagrams.

A2DD1F99EAA04F54A955AABE3DE6AE20.description:
Solve real-world and mathematical problems by writing and solving equations of the form x + p = q and px = q for cases in which p, q and x are all
nonnegative rational numbers.

DFE99A05CCEF4F708B8F5D4FE049A009.description:
Use variables to represent numbers and write expressions when solving a real-world or mathematical problem; understand that a variable can
represent an unknown number, or, depending on the purpose at hand, any number in a specified set.

D7F8FAF90B964EF5876DD9C55CD60D7D.description:
Understand solving an equation or inequality as a process of answering a question: which values from a specified set, if any, make the equation or
inequality true? Use substitution to determine whether a given number in a specified set makes an equation or inequality true.

D704474B060A443DAAD213A8A1F84442.description: Reason about and solve one-variable equations and inequalities.

D4AA27C240D54BF2A410913C5670392B.description:
Identify when two expressions are equivalent (i.e., when the two expressions name the same number regardless of which value is substituted into
them). For example, the expressions y + y + y and 3y are equivalent because they name the same number regardless of which number y stands for.

038A15D0473F4B62B719121CDE5C9CE8.description:
Evaluate expressions at specific values for their variables. Include expressions that arise from formulas in real-world problems. Perform
arithmetic operations, including those involving whole-number exponents, in the conventional order when there are no parentheses to
specify a particular order (Order of Operations). For example, use the formulas V = s^3 and A = 6 s^2 to find the volume and surface area of a
cube with sides of length s = 1/2.

7C8590F695CA420ABEC9CBDB43690700.description:
Identify parts of an expression using mathematical terms (sum, term, product, factor, quotient, coefficient); view one or more parts of an
expression as a single entity. For example, describe the expression 2(8 + 7) as a product of two factors; view (8 + 7) as both a single entity and
a sum of two terms.

CB3C4CD2493E4565B59F36DE26156AFB.description:
Write expressions that record operations with numbers and with letters standing for numbers. For example, express the calculation
“Subtract y from 5” as 5 – y.

54EFEEC4434E43EC8CFE0369250DBE4A.description: Write, read, and evaluate expressions in which letters stand for numbers.

267901CECB94447BA719D9E2CA738F77.description: Write and evaluate numerical expressions involving whole-number exponents.

6F777372683F4246A2711F638A2F8BCF.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of arithmetic to algebraic expressions.

2BC84AA751F1405CBD72B217B15D3526.description:
Solve real-world and mathematical problems by graphing points in all four quadrants of the coordinate plane. Include use of coordinates and
absolute value to find distances between points with the same first coordinate or the same second coordinate.

0858099863E54239A1CB0BDA30CEAF94.description:
Distinguish comparisons of absolute value from statements about order. For example, recognize that an account balance less than –30
dollars represents a debt greater than 30 dollars.

691328B0BF7340709C7BE6EA551F7239.description:
Understand the absolute value of a rational number as its distance from 0 on the number line; interpret absolute value as magnitude for a
positive or negative quantity in a real-world situation. For example, for an account balance of –30 dollars, write |–30| = 30 to describe the
size of the debt in dollars.

529C8D1D9AB14DB0AB48AA9DC12945A6.description:
Write, interpret, and explain statements of order for rational numbers in real-world contexts. For example, write –3°C > –7°C to express the
fact that –3°C is warmer than –7°C.

F3B92550E8EC4EE39B6F3FD6767A6C96.description:
Interpret statements of inequality as statements about the relative position of two numbers on a number line diagram. For example,
interpret –3 > –7 as a statement that –3 is located to the right of –7 on a number line oriented from left to right.

CF9AC59923D441429D44066FED971DB7.description: Understand ordering and absolute value of rational numbers.

707A8CD92028413ABD51CF20C6CE8A04.description:
Find and position integers and other rational numbers on a horizontal or vertical number line diagram; find and position pairs of integers and
other rational numbers on a coordinate plane.

38ED108932464F41A5D22D3B3809C360.description:
Understand signs of numbers in ordered pairs as indicating locations in quadrants of the coordinate plane; recognize that when two ordered
pairs differ only by signs, the locations of the points are related by reflections across one or both axes.

17CCAAA8DD8A4AD3945AB80DF21EE292.description:
Recognize opposite signs of numbers as indicating locations on opposite sides of 0 on the number line; recognize that the opposite of the
opposite of a number is the number itself, e.g., –(–3) = 3, and that 0 is its own opposite.

DA4D5064496445A09D8855A0233E945D.description:
Understand a rational number as a point on the number line. Extend number line diagrams and coordinate axes familiar from previous grades to
represent points on the line and in the plane with negative number coordinates.

07BBF265AE12469C9E91D224101B18DC.description:
Understand that positive and negative numbers are used together to describe quantities having opposite directions or values (e.g., temperature
above/below zero, elevation above/below sea level, debits/credits, positive/negative electric charge); use positive and negative numbers to
represent quantities in real-world contexts, explaining the meaning of 0 in each situation.

EB1491D603044E8FBE9FDB7DAB4B92CA.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of numbers to the system of rational numbers.

6E9A7DB3CC3F4230A41F35C999A573C9.description:
Find the greatest common factor of two whole numbers less than or equal to 100 and the least common multiple of two whole numbers less than or
equal to 12. Use the distributive property to express a sum of two whole numbers 1–100 with a common factor as a multiple of a sum of two whole
numbers with no common factor. For example, express 36 + 8 as 4 (9 + 2).

D10BD0E03CA64D3BA2B47591C001EEEF.description: Fluently add, subtract, multiply, and divide multi-digit decimals using the standard algorithm for each operation.

B3899A05FEAD4BAEAD7D90290376BF6D.description: Fluently divide multi-digit numbers using the standard algorithm.

B74F727016E14493A813ED4071BE333B.description: Compute fluently with multi-digit numbers and find common factors and multiples.

E82140CE0C394FF989A567E0B66371B6.description:
Interpret and compute quotients of fractions, and solve word problems involving division of fractions by fractions, e.g., by using visual fraction
models and equations to represent the problem. For example, create a story context for (2/3) ÷ (3/4) and use a visual fraction model to show the
quotient; use the relationship between multiplication and division to explain that (2/3) ÷ (3/4) = 8/9 because 3/4 of 8/9 is 2/3. (In general, (a/b) ÷ (c/d)
= ad/bc.) How much chocolate will each person get if 3 people share 1/2 lb of chocolate equally? How many 3/4-cup servings are in 2/3 of a cup of
yogurt? How wide is a rectangular strip of land with length 3/4 mi and area 1/2 square mi?

C1972C44FF2346F38D5FF6A71EE7B40D.description: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to divide fractions by fractions.

560CBB1CE86E46139FFF1805BCB198A2.description: Use ratio reasoning to convert measurement units; manipulate and transform units appropriately when multiplying or dividing quantities.

EEADCE1F5326466E85E40E08EDF0E254.description:
Find a percent of a quantity as a rate per 100 (e.g., 30% of a quantity means 30/100 times the quantity); solve problems involving finding the
whole given a part and the percent.

4FAA1ECA746E4DDAB6F13970C8A223D9.description:
Solve unit rate problems including those involving unit pricing and constant speed. For example, if it took 7 hours to mow 4 lawns, then at
that rate, how many lawns could be mowed in 35 hours? At what rate were lawns being mowed?

9593D2C498F84D4FAF614D5678630C77.description:
Make tables of equivalent ratios relating quantities with whole-number measurements, find missing values in the tables, and plot the pairs
of values on the coordinate plane. Use tables to compare ratios.

4D0A1D58E4444120AA322FAA1E32F338.description:
Use ratio and rate reasoning to solve real-world and mathematical problems, e.g., by reasoning about tables of equivalent ratios, tape diagrams,
double number line diagrams, or equations.

CB9572A9776048C2AB3E5058AD3C8BCF.description:
Understand the concept of a ratio and use ratio language to describe a ratio relationship between two quantities. For example, “The ratio of wings to
beaks in the bird house at the zoo was 2:1, because for every 2 wings there was 1 beak.” “For every vote candidate A received, candidate C received
nearly three votes.”

0B847EFDCA914D6CB1081C5ECB4824D6.description: Understand ratio concepts and use ratio reasoning to solve problems.

8F9C18C85BD24CDB937550B6002C2708.description: Survey the truths about mathematical objects that are interesting in their own right and independent of human opinions. CSGS4

C3BDEDFF60A74538BCAA7BB16154AC29.description: Recognize the power of the human mind as both a gift from God and a reflection of Him in whose image and likeness we are made. CSGS3

91BA28C053D643CE940420005498913E.description: Develop lines of inquiry (as developmentally appropriate) to understand why things are true and why they are false. CSGS2

0C984DBBFF7C489CB8B831CB75B0C35D.description: Develop the mental habits of precise, determined, careful, and accurate questioning, inquiry, and reasoning. CSGS1

37EB2F1E4B48455CA6963AB569D5B3FA.description: Look for and express regularity in repeated reasoning.

1C366590AB6A4881B7E4942E0606C792.description: CSDS2: Respond to the beauty, harmony, proportion, radiance, and wholeness present in mathematics.

31B82A81C78146739B19ED39737F1FFD.description: CSDS1: Display a sense of wonder about mathematical relationships as well as confidence in mathematical certitude.

64E5CEFFEC1E4F82A24C222655BCD8AE.description: Look for and make use of structure.

9A810A60F3364E2E9AE2051C0B6E3D20.description: CSDS5: Demonstrate an interest of the mental processes within mathematics (order, perseverance, and logical reasoning) and how these processes help develop natural virtues (self-discipline and fortitude).

506700298AC048479F1617015913701B.description: CSIS2: Demonstrate how sound logical arguments are foundational to mathematics.

5A3237DC358F4F9A8AD3D3FBE2C2A05A.description: CSDS5: Demonstrate an interest of the mental processes within mathematics (order, perseverance, and logical reasoning) and how these processes help develop natural virtues (self-discipline and fortitude).

82D8AAD1A95C4E46B82CDA7242A7F89E.description: Construct viable arguments and critique the reasoning of others.

B81DFDA5609F44E28018663362D41019.description: CSDS4: Exhibit joy at solving difficult mathematical problems and operations.

8B403798013345D680F5DC02BB8987B0.description: CSDS3: Show interest in the pursuit of understanding for its own sake.

72A5ECCFF4A744D18B9FABAF4CC50CF5.description: Make sense of problems and persevere in solving them.

60ECF605D718461C91A056DF820B1C34.description: STANDARDS FOR MATHEMATICAL PRACTICES AND CATHOLIC DISPOSITIONS
